Introduction¶

Beginning in the 1950s with simple designs and only a handful of parts, Legos have evolved to have complex sets with thousands of small pieces and expanding into covering famous themes such as Star Wars, Harry Potter, and Disney. Additionally, lego have come full circle as a brand and have made their own content based around their products through videogames, movies, and tv shows. One can learn more about the history of lego here.

This project is looking at legos as a product and how they have evolved over the years, going from a simple kids toy to elaborate collectors items and display pieces. As someone who grew up building legos, this transition has often fascinated me as I have seen them change over the years, constantly releasing new sets and developing a brand around display pieces with limited or no play ability such as city skylines and botanicals, which are quite different than the legos I remembered growing up with that focused on being able to play with them as a toy and creativity. That aspect of legos certainly motivated me to do this project around them, as I am curious to see if legos really have changed over the years or if it is just something I have been precieving as a change and not correctly rembering the past. I also think that the question of if legos have become more adult centered over the years is an important one to understand how it may or may not have effected them as a business with a potential change in marketing, as well as seeing where legos and other toys may be going in the future.

To start off this project, we will look at the raw data for this project.

Data Curation¶

The data we are using for this project is from rebrickable, which can be viewed here. This dataset was created from information on all lego sets past and present, and has information about the parts in all official lego sets ever created. It contains information about all the lego pieces required in all lego sets.

If one is particularly interested in legos in general, rebrickable also has some great resources on what lego sets can be built using pieces in other sets. Additionally, as lego themselves are constantly releasing new products, the database is constantly being updated to stay as up to date as possible.

To start, a majority of this project will involve pandas and its data frames, so we will need to import it along with some other models which we will touch on later. Pandas is a powerful data science tool built on top of python, that relies on data frames which are essentailly tables. More can be read up on pandas here.

Each row of the dataframe has the following data:

set_num - the official number lego has given the set

name - the name of the lego set

year - the year it was first made

theme_id - the id number for the corresponding theme the set is in, as used in the data set

num_parts - the number of individual lego pieces in the set

image_url - a link to a picture of the box for the lego set. This piece of data is not so necessary for our data analysis, so we can drop it from the dataframe

Additionally, for sets listed as being past 2023 (so with 2024 or 2025 release dates), we will drop them because the entire year has yet to pass, so including them will mess up some of the yearly data beacuse each prior year will have had data for the whole year, while 2024 and 2025 have much less sets listed because 2024 is not yet finished.

In [ ]:
setsdf = setsdf.drop(columns=['img_url'])
setsdf = setsdf.drop(setsdf[setsdf['year'] > 2023].index)

A hypothesis we can test from this is if all the themes have roughly the same number of lego sets, which can be tested by a chi squared or goodness of fit test. For this test, the null is that all themes have the same number of sets, and the alternative hypothesis is that they have different numbers of sets. More can be read about how chi squared tests work here. In order to run the test, we can use the chisquare function from scipy.stats, which we imported earlier, and as the function is shown below to get a meaninful output.

In [ ]:
chi2_stat, p_value = chisquare(themes)
print(chi2_stat)
print(p_value)

65127.32042298382
0.0

Here, as we would expect, we find a very high chi2 statistic, and a low p value, meaning that the null hypothesis is rejected, and the number of sets in each theme is not the same at a statstically significant level, which would be expected as we see some themes are much larger than others.

Primary Analysis and Visualizations¶

Next we shall begin looking at some machine learning methods to get some more meaningful conclusions about how legos have changed over time. As our main question is looking at how sets have shifted to also cater towards adults more, we can look at how sets have become more complex and have had more pieces over the years.

K Means¶

While we are trying to classify these lego sets into sets for adults and for kids, there isn't exactly a specific classification given for each of them. Therefore, this is an unspervised learning classification problem, meaning that we need to create our own classifications becuase none are predetermined. We do this by looking at the data and finding ways to split it up. For this tutorial, we will split the data up with the k means algorithm, where the data is split into k clusters, each centered around a specific mean in the data. The algorithm works in a way that each point has a minimal distance to its mean while also having a maximal distance from the points in the other group, to establish clear groupings. More can be read on the process here.

Additionally, while this can be done with data of any number of dimensions and is often done with several dimensions, we will only be creating means in a one dimensional data set of the number of pieces each set has. We will be creating two clusters, with one being smaller sets intended for kids, and the other being larger sets intended for adults.

To run the actual algorithm, we will be using the KMeans class from the sklearn library of python. The documentation of this class can be read up on here.

In [ ]:
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=2, random_state=0, n_init="auto").fit(setsdf[['num_parts']])
means = kmeans.cluster_centers_
means
Out[ ]:
array([[ 112.12906058],
       [2163.44781784]])

This result from the algorithm shows that the split of clusters from the two groups uses means centered around 112 and 2163 pieces, with the smaller one being our grouping of sets made for kids, and the larger one being our grouping of sets made for adults. Now we can add the category of a set as a small set or large set to our dataframe.

In [ ]:
setsdf.insert(2, "category", kmeans.labels_, True)
setsdf['small set'] = setsdf['category'] == 0
setsdf['big set'] = setsdf['category'] == 1

Linear Regressions¶

Next, we will examine this relationship between the number of parts in a set with the year it is released with some linear regression models. Linear regressions are powerful tools to understand the correlation between two different pieces of data, where a line of the form y = mX + b is made from the input data to output data in a way that it is best fit, which is determined by having a line that has the smallest sum of squared errors in the data, where the error is determined as the distance from an actual y value to the prediction the model gives from its X value.

Some more information on the basics of linear regressions can be found here.

If you are interested in how computers actually solve linear least squares problems to get linear regression results, information can be found on that here.

In order to acually solve do linear regressions, we will be using the LinearRegression class from the sklearn library, which we imported earlier, and more can be read up on that class here.

In [ ]:
reg = LinearRegression().fit(setsdf[['year']],setsdf['num_parts'])
reg.coef_
Out[ ]:
array([3.12021043])
In [ ]:
reg.score(setsdf[['year']],setsdf['num_parts'])
Out[ ]:
0.010734142121439305

This regression shows that each year the number of parts in each set on average is increasing by 3.1202 pieces. However, as we can see with the R squared score which captures the variance in y that is correlated to x, it is quite low at .0107, meaning that only 1 percent of the variation in number of pieces per set can be found from the year, and there really isn't a very strong trend upwards, making it difficult to draw conclusions from this data.

In [ ]:
setsdf.plot(x='year', y='num_parts', style='.',ylabel = 'number of parts per set', title = 'Number of parts per set each year')
Out[ ]:
<Axes: title={'center': 'Number of parts per set each year'}, xlabel='year', ylabel='number of parts per set'>

As we have seen in previous analysis and the plot above, the number of sets in general has gone up a lot over time, so while the number of and size of large sets has certainly gone up a lot over the years, so has the number of small sets, which can be bringing down the average number of pieces in each set. Therefore, in order to truly capture the scope of how big legos have grown over time, we can look at instead how the largest set each year has grown, as to not be dragged down by the increasing number of sets in general each year.

Conclusions¶

So, looking at legos over time it is clear to see that they have evolved a lot from when they first stated out. Not only are there larger being made now than when lego first started as we have seen multiple times through the data, the variety of legos in general has really exploded over the past 25 years. The number of themes lego has show this very well, as legos have a strong reach across a great spectrum of possibilities for the brick built world. Additionally the willingness of lego to create larger sets opens them up for more possibilities. Since I first got my first lego set back in 2010, I have seen the brand do many exciting new things.

But, relating back to my original research question of if legos have become more adult centered, what I will say is it is complicated. I have shown that legos have created more large sets, and the expansion of themes does often include themes that are more focused for the nice interests of adults and collectors looking for legos as a display piece rather than a toy to play with. In the way that large sets with thousands of pieces are more common today than ever before, I would say that legos are more focused on adults as an audience now than they were when they first started, creating sets that require lots of focus and attention (not to mention hefty price tags) that are often a barrier for kids to get these giant sets, that are instead clearly marketed for adults.

That being said, the data also shows that legos of all types are more prevelant now than before. While there are more larger sets, there are also more smaller sets, and while some of the new themes are centered around being display pieces and valuable collectables, there are also many new themes which emphasize playability and accessibility for younger kids to enjoy them (speaking more from my personal knowledge and not so much the data here). Perhaps a more accurate way of stating it is that legos as a brand have branched into many different areas, and adding adding larger sets for adults as collector items is simply one of the ways it is branching out.

Anyways, I hope you enjoyed this and were able to learn a bit about legos and/or the data science and machine learning process.
